<task id="023" project="sdap-bff-api-remediation-fix">
  <metadata>
    <title>Multi-identity credential refactor — DI-singleton TokenCredential</title>
    <status>in-progress</status>
    <estimated-effort>2 hours</estimated-effort>
    <assigned>AI agent (code change)</assigned>
    <started>2026-05-24</started>
    <completed></completed>
    <tags>bff-api, auth, refactor, di, phase-2.5, urgent</tags>
    <parallel-group>none</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>Touches 18+ services; sequential to allow build verification between batches</parallel-reason>
    <rigor>FULL</rigor>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Architectural fix for an auth-r2 follow-on bug discovered during the 2026-05-24 cutover spot-check.

    Bug: 20+ BFF services construct `new DefaultAzureCredential()` without specifying which UAMI to use.
    On multi-identity App Services (System-Assigned + UAMI both attached), the credential chain fails
    with "Unable to load the proper Managed Identity." Surfaced as `[useAiSummary] Failed to resolve
    playbook: HTTP 500` from PlaybookService.cs:58 after cutover to new Linux dev.

    Fix (NOT a band-aid): register `Azure.Core.TokenCredential` as a DI singleton in Program.cs that
    delegates to `ManagedIdentityCredentialFactory.Create(config)`. Refactor every affected service
    to inject `TokenCredential` via constructor instead of constructing its own. Centralizes auth so
    a future credential pattern change is one file, not 20.

    User explicitly rejected helper-band-aid approach: "we don't want to just revert back we need to
    actually fix the issue."
  </prompt>

  <role>BFF .NET refactor — DI patterns + auth construction.</role>

  <goal>
    All BFF services that need outbound auth to Dataverse / Cosmos / OpenAI / AI Foundry inject
    `TokenCredential` via constructor. Zero `new DefaultAzureCredential()` call sites in production
    BFF code after this task (exception: GraphClientFactory which has its own complex ClientSecret +
    MI dual path). The Spaarke.Dataverse cross-assembly case handled via optional constructor param
    with fallback to ClientSecretCredential when configured.

    User retests document upload + AI summary → succeeds end-to-end on new Linux dev.
  </goal>

  <inputs>
    <file purpose="canonical-pattern">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/Graph/GraphClientFactory.cs</file>
    <file purpose="helper">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/Auth/ManagedIdentityCredentialFactory.cs</file>
    <file purpose="recovery-doc">projects/sdap-bff-api-remediation-fix/current-task.md</file>
  </inputs>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="user direction 2026-05-24">Fix root cause, not symptom. Architectural refactor over inline band-aid.</constraint>
    <constraint source="Spaarke.Core CLAUDE.md">Keep Libraries Focused — helper stays in BFF, NOT in Spaarke.Core.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-010">DI minimalism — registering 1 singleton TokenCredential satisfies this (no new interface).</constraint>
    <constraint source="auth-r2 reality">UAMI mi-bff-api-dev is the canonical auth principal per the BFF's Graph:ManagedIdentity:ClientId config setting.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>projects/sdap-bff-api-remediation-fix/current-task.md (Mini-Plan section)</file>
      <file>projects/sdap-bff-api-remediation-fix/baseline/linux-dev-migration.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/Graph/GraphClientFactory.cs (lines 117-132)</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-028-spaarke-auth-architecture.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      Surfaced during cutover spot-check 2026-05-24 evening. PlaybookService → Dataverse failed with
      ManagedIdentityCredential "Unable to load the proper Managed Identity." Root cause: new Linux
      dev had BOTH System-Assigned and User-Assigned MIs enabled; `DefaultAzureCredential` without
      ClientId can't disambiguate. Removing SAM (`az webapp identity remove`) was a tactical step but
      doesn't fix the underlying code anti-pattern that will re-bite when any env attaches multiple
      identities (e.g., when customer deployments have both).

      The proper fix is to make per-service credential construction impossible — centralize via DI
      singleton injection. This task does that.

      Discovered as a "Phase 2.5" issue between Phase 2 gate and Phase 3 baseline — NOT in original
      project scope but now in-scope per user direction "since this is part of the bff.api then it
      should be in this project."
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="019" status="completed">Linux dev migration (required for the bug to surface)</dependency>
      <dependency task="022" status="completed">Phase 2 gate — needed to be past gate to discover this</dependency>
    </dependencies>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">✅ Create `Infrastructure/Auth/ManagedIdentityCredentialFactory.cs` with `Create(IConfiguration)` static method that reads `Graph:ManagedIdentity:ClientId` (fallback `ManagedIdentity:ClientId`) and constructs DefaultAzureCredential with the ClientId pinned via DefaultAzureCredentialOptions.</step>
    <step order="2">✅ Register `Azure.Core.TokenCredential` as DI singleton in Program.cs that calls the helper.</step>
    <step order="3">Refactor each of 18 services in `current-task.md` Mini-Plan "Files to refactor" list to inject `TokenCredential` via constructor instead of constructing it. Pattern: add `TokenCredential credential` constructor param, replace `_credential = new DefaultAzureCredential();` with `_credential = credential;`. Use `using Azure.Core;`. Remove `using Azure.Identity;` if no other usage.</step>
    <step order="4">For DI module factories (`AiPersistenceModule`, `AiModule`), change `services.AddSingleton(_ => ...)` to `services.AddSingleton(sp => ...)` and use `sp.GetRequiredService&lt;TokenCredential&gt;()` inside the factory.</step>
    <step order="5">For services with mid-flight credential construction (`AgentServiceClient.CreateAgentsClient`, `SessionRestoreService`), promote credential to a constructor-injected field, then use the field.</step>
    <step order="6">For Spaarke.Dataverse/DataverseAccessDataSource.cs: add optional `TokenCredential? credential = null` constructor param. Use the injected credential for the MI path (when no ClientSecret available). Preserve the ClientSecretCredential + OBO logic unchanged.</step>
    <step order="7">Build: `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/` — must compile clean.</step>
    <step order="8">Run unit tests: `dotnet test tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/` — fix any constructor mocks broken by added TokenCredential param (use Moq's `Mock&lt;TokenCredential&gt;()` or pass DefaultAzureCredential directly for the test).</step>
    <step order="9">Deploy: `./scripts/Deploy-BffApi.ps1 -ResourceGroupName rg-spaarke-dev -AppServiceName spaarke-bff-dev`</step>
    <step order="10">Verify: `/healthz` 200, `/healthz/dataverse` 200, user retest of document upload + AI summary succeeds end-to-end</step>
    <step order="11">Commit: `feat(sdap-bff-api-remediation): task 023 - architectural fix for multi-identity credential ambiguity`</step>
    <step order="12">Update TASK-INDEX.md to add 023 as ✅</step>
    <step order="13">Update CLAUDE.md Project Status to "Phase 3 READY (post-task-023)"</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="Read/Edit">file-by-file refactor</tool>
    <tool name="dotnet">build + test</tool>
    <tool name="Deploy-BffApi.ps1">deploy</tool>
    <tool name="curl">verify endpoints</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="code">Infrastructure/Auth/ManagedIdentityCredentialFactory.cs (NEW)</output>
    <output type="code">Program.cs (TokenCredential singleton registered)</output>
    <output type="code">18 service files refactored to inject TokenCredential</output>
    <output type="code">Spaarke.Dataverse/DataverseAccessDataSource.cs (optional TokenCredential param)</output>
    <output type="docs">projects/sdap-bff-api-remediation-fix/current-task.md (updated)</output>
    <output type="docs">tasks/TASK-INDEX.md (023 added as ✅)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">Zero `new DefaultAzureCredential()` call sites in BFF production code (exception: GraphClientFactory's complex dual-path logic preserved)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dotnet build` clean (warnings within Phase 0 baseline)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">All unit tests pass (constructor mocks updated where needed)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`/healthz` 200, `/healthz/dataverse` 200 on spaarke-bff-dev post-deploy</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">User document upload + AI summary works end-to-end on new dev (manual verification)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Multi-identity safe: works whether App Service has UAMI-only, UAMI+SAM, or just SAM</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    <discovery-context>
      Discovered 2026-05-24 evening during cutover spot-check. User had set Dataverse env var sprk_BffApiBaseUrl to new dev URL; opened document upload UI; useAiSummary hook called playbook resolve endpoint which 500'd. Logs showed PlaybookService.EnsureAuthenticatedAsync failing with "Unable to load the proper Managed Identity" — root cause traced to `new DefaultAzureCredential()` without UAMI ClientId on multi-identity App Service.
    </discovery-context>
    <related-finding>
      auth-r2 docs drift fix (docs/guides/auth-deployment-setup.md SAM → UAMI) was committed in cutover commit 2066b98e. This task is the CODE counterpart to that documentation fix.
    </related-finding>
  </notes>
</task>
